# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: threejs
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:threejs/api-webgl-api] Support for WebGL is present in all modern browsers (see the compatibility tables below); however, the user's device must also have hardware that supports these features.
[src:threejs/api-webgl-api] The WebGL 2 API introduces support for much of the OpenGL ES 3.0 feature set; it's provided through the `WebGL2RenderingContext` interface.
[src:threejs/api-webgl-api] The `<canvas>` element is also used by the Canvas API to do 2D graphics on web pages.
[src:threejs/api-webgl-api] WebGL 2 is a major update to WebGL which is provided through the `WebGL2RenderingContext` interface.
[src:threejs/api-webgl-api] See also the blog post "WebGL 2 lands in Firefox" and webglsamples.org/WebGL2Samples for a few demos.
[src:threejs/api-webgl-api] Below, you'll find an assortment of guides to help you learn WebGL concepts and tutorials that offer step-by-step lessons and examples.
[src:threejs/api-webgl-api] A guide to variables, buffers, and other types of data used when writing WebGL code.
[src:threejs/api-webgl-api] Tips and suggestions to help you improve the quality, performance, and reliability of your WebGL content.
[src:threejs/api-webgl-api] A beginner's guide to WebGL core concepts.
[src:threejs/api-webgl-api] A good place to start if you don't have previous WebGL experience.
[src:threejs/api-webgl-api] This example demonstrates the simple animation of a one-color shape.
[src:threejs/api-webgl-api] Topics examined are adapting to aspect ratio differences, a function to build shader programs from sets of multiple shaders, and the basics of drawing in WebGL.
[src:threejs/api-webgl-api] A series of live samples with short explanations that showcase WebGL concepts and capabilities.
[src:threejs/api-webgl-api] The examples are sorted according to topic and level of difficulty, covering the WebGL rendering context, shader programming, textures, geometry, user interaction, and more.
[src:threejs/api-webgl-api] How to enable and use compressed texture formats for better memory performance.
[src:threejs/api-webgl-api] A detailed explanation of the three core matrices that are typically used to represent a 3D object view: the model, view and projection matrices.
[src:threejs/api-webgl-api] A useful guide to how 3D transform matrices work, and can be used on the web — both for WebGL calculations and in CSS transforms.
[src:threejs/api-webgl-api] In addition to the browser, the GPU itself also needs to support the feature.
[src:threejs/api-webgl-api] So, for example, S3 Texture Compression (S3TC) is only available on Tegra-based tablets.
[src:threejs/api-webgl-api] Most browsers make the WebGL context available through the `webgl` context name, but older ones need `experimental-webgl` as well.
[src:threejs/api-webgl-api] In addition, the upcoming WebGL 2 is fully backwards-compatible and will have the context name `webgl2`.
[src:threejs/api-webgl-api] A Boolean property that, when `true`, enables a minimum capability mode.
[src:threejs/api-webgl-api] When in this mode, WebGL is configured to only support the bare minimum feature set and capabilities required by the WebGL specification.
[src:threejs/api-webgl-api] This lets you ensure that your WebGL code will work on any device or browser, regardless of their capabilities.
[src:threejs/api-webgl-api] A Boolean property that, when `true`, disables all WebGL extensions.
[src:threejs/three-js] Three.js allows the creation of graphical processing unit (GPU)-accelerated 3D animations using the JavaScript language as part of a website without relying on proprietary browser plugins.
[src:threejs/three-js] This is possible due to the advent of WebGL, a low-level graphics API created specifically for the web.
[src:threejs/three-js] High-level libraries such as Three.js, Babylon.js, Verge3D and many more make it possible to author complex 3D computer animations for display in the browser without the effort required for a traditional standalone application or a plugin.
[src:threejs/three-js] Three.js was first released by Ricardo Cabello on GitHub in April 2010.
[src:threejs/three-js] The origins of the library can be traced back to his involvement with the demoscene in the early 2000s.
[src:threejs/three-js] The code was originally developed in the ActionScript language used by Adobe Flash, later being ported to JavaScript in 2009.
[src:threejs/three-js] In Cabello's mind, there were two strong points that justified the shift away from ActionScript: Firstly, JavaScript provided greater platform independence.
[src:threejs/three-js] Secondly, applications written in JavaScript would not need to be compiled by the developer beforehand, unlike Flash applications.
[src:threejs/three-js] Additional contributions by Cabello include API design, CanvasRenderer, SVGRenderer, and being responsible for merging the commits by the various contributors into the project.
[src:threejs/three-js] With the advent of WebGL, Paul Brunt was able to implement the new rendering technology quite easily as Three.js was designed with the rendering code as a module rather than in the core itself.
[src:threejs/three-js] Branislav Uličný, an early contributor, started with Three.js in 2010 after having posted a number of WebGL demos on his own site.
[src:threejs/three-js] He wanted WebGL renderer capabilities in Three.js to exceed those of CanvasRenderer or SVGRenderer.
[src:threejs/three-js] His major contributions generally involve materials, shaders, and post-processing.
[src:threejs/three-js] Soon after the introduction of WebGL 1.0 on Firefox 4 in March 2011, Joshua Koo came on board.
[src:threejs/three-js] He built his first Three.js demo for 3D text in September 2011.
[src:threejs/three-js] His contributions frequently relate to geometry generation.
[src:threejs/three-js] Starting from version 118, Three.js uses WebGL 2.0 by default.
[src:threejs/three-js] Three.js has over 2000 contributors on GitHub.
[src:threejs/three-js] Three.js runs in all browsers with support for WebGL 2.0.
[src:threejs/three-js] Three.js is made available under the MIT License.
[src:threejs/webgl-api-tutorial] This tutorial describes how to use the `<canvas>` element to draw WebGL graphics, starting with the basics.
[src:threejs/webgl-api-tutorial] The examples provided should give you some clear ideas of what you can do with WebGL and will provide code snippets that may get you started in building your own content.
[src:threejs/webgl-api-tutorial] WebGL enables web content to use an API based on OpenGL ES 2.0 to perform 3D rendering in an HTML `<canvas>` in browsers that support it without the use of plug-ins.
[src:threejs/webgl-api-tutorial] WebGL programs consist of control code written in JavaScript and special effects code (shader code) that is executed on a computer's Graphics Processing Unit (GPU).
[src:threejs/webgl-api-tutorial] WebGL elements can be mixed with other HTML elements and composited with other parts of the page or page background.
[src:threejs/webgl-api-tutorial] Using the `<canvas>` element is not very difficult, but you do need a basic understanding of HTML and JavaScript.
[src:threejs/webgl-api-tutorial] The `<canvas>` element and WebGL are not supported in some older browsers, but are supported in recent versions of all major browsers.
[src:threejs/webgl-api-tutorial] In order to draw graphics on the canvas we use a JavaScript context object, which creates graphics on the fly.
[src:threejs/webgl-api-tutorial] How to render simple flat shapes using WebGL.
[src:threejs/webgl-api-tutorial] Demonstrates how to add color to shapes using shaders.
[src:threejs/webgl-api-tutorial] Shows how to rotate and translate objects to create simple animations.
[src:threejs/webgl-api-tutorial] Shows how to create and animate a 3D object (in this case, a cube).
[src:threejs/webgl-api-tutorial] Demonstrates how to map textures onto the faces of an object.
[src:threejs/webgl-api-tutorial] How to simulate lighting effects in your WebGL context.
[src:threejs/webgl-api-tutorial] Shows how to animate textures; in this case, by mapping an Ogg video onto the faces of a rotating cube.
[src:threejs/webgl] WebGL programs consist of control code written in JavaScript, and shader code written in OpenGL ES Shading Language (GLSL ES, sometimes referred to as ESSL), a language similar to C or C++.
[src:threejs/webgl] WebGL code is executed on a computer's GPU.
[src:threejs/webgl] WebGL is designed and maintained by the non-profit Khronos Group.
[src:threejs/webgl] On February 9, 2022, Khronos Group announced WebGL 2.0 support from all major browsers.
[src:threejs/webgl] From 2024, a new graphics API, WebGPU, is being developed to supersede WebGL.
[src:threejs/webgl] WebGPU provides extended capabilities, a more modern interface, and direct GPU access, which is useful for demanding graphics as well as AI applications.
[src:threejs/webgl] WebGL 1.0 is based on OpenGL ES 2.0 and provides an API for 3D graphics.
[src:threejs/webgl] It uses the HTML5 canvas element and is accessed using Document Object Model (DOM) interfaces.
[src:threejs/webgl] It guarantees the availability of many optional extensions of WebGL 1.0, and exposes new APIs.
[src:threejs/webgl] Automatic memory management is provided implicitly by JavaScript.
[src:threejs/webgl] Like OpenGL ES 2.0, WebGL lacks the fixed-function APIs introduced in OpenGL 1.0 and deprecated in OpenGL 3.0.
[src:threejs/webgl] This functionality, if required, has to be implemented by the developer using shader code and JavaScript.
[src:threejs/webgl] Shaders in WebGL are written in GLSL and passed to the WebGL API as text strings.
[src:threejs/webgl] The WebGL implementation compiles these strings to GPU code.
[src:threejs/webgl] This code is executed for each vertex sent through the API and for each pixel rasterized to the screen.
[src:threejs/webgl] WebGL evolved out of the Canvas 3D experiments started by Vladimir Vukićević at Mozilla.
[src:threejs/webgl] Vukićević first demonstrated a Canvas 3D prototype in 2006.
[src:threejs/webgl] By the end of 2007, both Mozilla and Opera had made their own separate implementations.
[src:threejs/webgl] In early 2009, the non-profit technology consortium Khronos Group started the WebGL Working Group, with initial participation from Apple, Google, Mozilla, Opera, and others.
[src:threejs/webgl] Version 1.0 of the WebGL specification was released March 2011.
[src:threejs/webgl] An early application of WebGL was Zygote Body.
[src:threejs/webgl] In November 2012 Autodesk announced that they ported most of their applications to the cloud running on local WebGL clients.
[src:threejs/webgl] These applications included Autodesk Fusion and AutoCAD.
[src:threejs/webgl] Development of the WebGL 2 specification started in 2013 and finished in January 2017.
[src:threejs/webgl] The specification is based on OpenGL ES 3.0.
[src:threejs/webgl] First implementations are in Firefox 51, Chrome 56 and Opera 43.
[src:threejs/webgl] Almost Native Graphics Layer Engine (ANGLE) is an open source graphic engine which implements WebGL 1.0 (2.0 which closely conforms to ES 3.0) and OpenGL ES 2.0 and 3.0 standards.
[src:threejs/webgl] It is a default backend for both Google Chrome and Mozilla Firefox on Windows platforms and works by translating WebGL and OpenGL calls to available platform-specific APIs.
[src:threejs/webgl] WebGL is widely supported by modern browsers.
[src:threejs/webgl] However, its availability depends on other factors, too, like whether the GPU supports it.
[src:threejs/webgl] The official WebGL website offers a simple test page.
[src:threejs/webgl] More detailed information (like what renderer the browser uses, and what extensions are available) can be found at third-party websites.
[src:threejs/webgl] Some such libraries were ported to JavaScript from other languages.
[src:threejs/webgl] Examples of libraries that provide high-level features include A-Frame (VR), BabylonJS, PlayCanvas, three.js, OSG.JS, Google’s model-viewer and CopperLicht.
[src:threejs/webgl] Web3D also made a project called X3DOM to make X3D and VRML content run on WebGL.
[src:threejs/webgl] There has been an emergence of 2D and 3D game engines for WebGL, such as Unreal Engine 4 and Unity.
[src:threejs/webgl] The Stage3D/Flash-based Away3D high-level library also has a port to WebGL via TypeScript.
[src:threejs/webgl] A more light-weight utility library that provides just the vector and matrix math utilities for shaders is sylvester.js.
[src:threejs/webgl] It is sometimes used in conjunction with a WebGL specific extension called glUtils.js.
[src:threejs/webgl] There are also some 2D libraries built atop WebGL, like Cocos2d-x or Pixi.js, which were implemented this way for performance reasons in a move that parallels what happened with the Starling Framework over Stage3D in the Flash world.
[src:threejs/webgl] The WebGL-based 2D libraries fall back to HTML5 canvas when WebGL is not available.
[src:threejs/webgl] Removing the rendering bottleneck by giving almost direct access to the GPU has exposed performance limitations in the JavaScript implementations.
[src:threejs/webgl] Some were addressed by asm.js and WebAssembly (similarly, the introduction of Stage3D exposed performance problems within ActionScript, which were addressed by projects like CrossBridge).
[src:threejs/webgl] As with any other graphics API, creating content for WebGL scenes requires using a 3D content creation tool and exporting the scene to a format that is readable by the viewer or helper library.
[src:threejs/webgl] Desktop 3D authoring software such as Blender, Autodesk Maya or SimLab Composer can be used for this purpose.
[src:threejs/webgl] In particular, Blend4Web allows a WebGL scene to be authored entirely in Blender and exported to a browser with a single click, even as a standalone web page.
[src:threejs/webgl] There are also some WebGL-specific software such as CopperCube and the online WebGL-based editor Clara.io.
[src:threejs/webgl] Online platforms such as Sketchfab and Clara.io allow users to directly upload their 3D models and display them using a hosted WebGL viewer.
[src:threejs/webgl] Starting from Firefox Version 27, Mozilla has given Firefox built-in WebGL tools that allow the editing of vertices and fragment shaders.
[src:threejs/webgl] A number of other debugging and profiling tools have also emerged.
[src:threejs/webglrenderingcontext] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:threejs/webglrenderingcontext] It’s been available across browsers since July 2015.
[src:threejs/webglrenderingcontext] The **`WebGLRenderingContext`** interface provides an interface to the OpenGL ES 2.0 graphics rendering context for the drawing surface of an HTML `<canvas>` element.
[src:threejs/webglrenderingcontext] Once you have the WebGL rendering context for a canvas, you can render within it.
[src:threejs/webglrenderingcontext] The WebGL tutorial has more information, examples, and resources on how to get started with WebGL.
[src:threejs/webglrenderingcontext] If you require a WebGL 2.0 context, see `WebGL2RenderingContext`; this supplies access to an implementation of OpenGL ES 3.0 graphics.
[src:threejs/webglrenderingcontext] A read-only back-reference to the `HTMLCanvasElement`.
[src:threejs/webglrenderingcontext] Might be `null` if it is not associated with a `<canvas>` element.
[src:threejs/webglrenderingcontext] The read-only width of the current drawing buffer.
[src:threejs/webglrenderingcontext] Should match the width of the canvas element associated with this context.
[src:threejs/webglrenderingcontext] The read-only height of the current drawing buffer.
[src:threejs/webglrenderingcontext] Should match the height of the canvas element associated with this context.
[src:threejs/webglrenderingcontext] Returns a `WebGLContextAttributes` object that contains the actual context parameters.
[src:threejs/webglrenderingcontext] Might return `null`, if the context is lost.
[src:threejs/webglrenderingcontext] Returns `true` if the context is lost, otherwise returns `false`.
[src:threejs/webglrenderingcontext] Ensures the context is compatible with the user's XR hardware, re-creating the context if necessary with a new configuration to do so.
[src:threejs/webglrenderingcontext] This can be used to start an application using standard 2D presentation, then transition to using a VR or AR mode later.
[src:threejs/webglrenderingcontext] Sets the source and destination blending factors.
[src:threejs/webglrenderingcontext] Sets both the RGB blend equation and alpha blend equation to a single equation.
[src:threejs/webglrenderingcontext] Sets the RGB blend equation and alpha blend equation separately.
[src:threejs/webglrenderingcontext] Defines which function is used for blending pixel arithmetic.
[src:threejs/webglrenderingcontext] Defines which function is used for blending pixel arithmetic for RGB and alpha components separately.
[src:threejs/webglrenderingcontext] Specifies the color values used when clearing color buffers.
[src:threejs/webglrenderingcontext] Specifies the depth value used when clearing the depth buffer.
[src:threejs/webglrenderingcontext] Specifies the stencil value used when clearing the stencil buffer.
[src:threejs/webglrenderingcontext] Sets which color components to enable or to disable when drawing or rendering to a `WebGLFramebuffer`.
[src:threejs/webglrenderingcontext] Specifies whether or not front- and/or back-facing polygons can be culled.
[src:threejs/webglrenderingcontext] Specifies a function that compares incoming pixel depth to the current depth buffer value.
[src:threejs/webglrenderingcontext] Sets whether writing into the depth buffer is enabled or disabled.
[src:threejs/webglrenderingcontext] Specifies the depth range mapping from normalized device coordinates to window or viewport coordinates.
[src:threejs/webglrenderingcontext] Disables specific WebGL capabilities for this context.
[src:threejs/webglrenderingcontext] Enables specific WebGL capabilities for this context.
[src:threejs/webglrenderingcontext] Specifies whether polygons are front- or back-facing by setting a winding orientation.
